int32_t gaia::telephony::NeighboringCellInfo::getCid ( ) const
Returns:
cell id in GSM, 0xffff max legal value UNKNOWN_CID if in UMTS or CDMA or unknown
int32_t gaia::telephony::NeighboringCellInfo::getLac ( ) const
Returns:
LAC in GSM, 0xffff max legal value UNKNOWN_CID if in UMTS or CMDA or unknown
TelephonyManager::NETWORK_TYPE gaia::telephony::NeighboringCellInfo::getNetworkType ( ) const
Returns:
Radio network type while neighboring cell location is stored.

Return TelephonyManager.NETWORK_TYPE_UNKNOWN means that the location information is unavailable.

Return TelephonyManager.NETWORK_TYPE_GPRS or TelephonyManager.NETWORK_TYPE_EDGE means that Neighboring Cell information is stored for GSM network, in which {NeighboringCellInfo.getLac} and {NeighboringCellInfo.getCid} should be called to access location.

Return TelephonyManager.NETWORK_TYPE_UMTS, TelephonyManager.NETWORK_TYPE_HSDPA, TelephonyManager.NETWORK_TYPE_HSUPA, or TelephonyManager.NETWORK_TYPE_HSPA means that Neighboring Cell information is stored for UMTS network, in which {NeighboringCellInfo.getPsc} should be called to access location.

int32_t gaia::telephony::NeighboringCellInfo::getPsc ( ) const
Returns:
Primary Scrambling Code in 9 bits format in UMTS, 0x1ff max value UNKNOWN_CID if in GSM or CMDA or unknown
int32_t gaia::telephony::NeighboringCellInfo::getRssi ( ) const
Returns:
received signal strength or UNKNOWN_RSSI if unknown

For GSM, it is in "asu" ranging from 0 to 31 (dBm = -113 + 2*asu) 0 means "-113 dBm or less" and 31 means "-51 dBm or greater" For UMTS, it is the Level index of CPICH RSCP defined in TS 25.125
